'''Māras''' ({{IPA-lv|mɑːras̪|}})  or '''Māra Day''' (sometimes referred as '''Great Māra Day''' or '''Mother Day''') was a [[Latvians|Latvian]] festival, devoted to [[Māra]], an ancient deity, and was celebrated on [[15 August]].  According to [[Sun|solar]] calendar, Māras marks the midpoint between [[Jāņi]], which is summer [[solstice]], and [[Miķeļi]], that represents the end of the harvest season. The actual date, likely, is the result of [[Christianity|Christian]] influence, identifying Māra with [[Virgin Mary]], whose devoted holiday ([[Assumption of Mary]]) is observed on 15 August.

